# Task: AI Detection (Punctuation, Structure & Language)

**Scope:** AI-specific patterns ONLY. This task does NOT cover:
- Wordiness/weak verbs (→ `word_choice.prompt`)
- Sentence rhythm/monotony (→ `sentence_analysis.prompt`)
- Passive voice issues (→ `sentence_analysis.prompt`)

**Model:** Haiku (pattern recognition for both punctuation and language patterns)

**Output:**
- `notes/ai_detection.md` — Pattern identification (what was found), severity-sorted
- `notes/simplifications.md` — Suggested fixes (stylistic, NOT auto-applied)

**Output Mode:** APPEND — do not overwrite existing content

**⚠️ These are SUGGESTIONS, not auto-fixes.** Unlike grammar errors, stylistic issues require author judgment.

---

## Flags

**`--only-issues`**: When this flag is passed, suppress all entries where the verdict is "pass" or "no issues found." Output only entries with actionable flags.

---

Read `../references/writing_quality_standards.md` Sections II–IV for the LLM-vs-human contrasts, severity tiers, and AI tell patterns (Parts A, B, C).

---

## Section Format

When analyzing a file, append to BOTH `ai_detection.md` and `simplifications.md`.

**ai_detection.md:**
```markdown
## [filename.tex]
<!-- Entries sorted: Critical → High → Medium → Low; document order within tier -->
### Critical
[checklist items with severity label...]
### High
[checklist items with severity label...]
### Medium
[checklist items with severity label...]
### Low
[checklist items with severity label...]
<!-- Omit any tier heading that has no entries -->
```

**simplifications.md:**
```markdown
## [filename.tex]
[Proposed revisions with explanations — organized by priority]
```

---

## Output Format (Checklist)

**CRITICAL:** Original and Proposed Revision must show COMPLETE SENTENCES — never truncate mid-sentence. This enables batch application via `apply_marked.prompt`.

**CRITICAL:** Before writing any Proposed Revision, run the full surface critic procedure on it: read @prompts/shared/components/surface_critic.prompt and follow (1) the surface rules (proposal context) and (2) the Self-Critic Pass (Tests 1–6). If any test fails structurally, emit the flag-only shape instead of a Proposed Revision. For this task, focus on R-NEW-CLAIMS (Test 4) and R-WEAK-FOR-WEAK (Test 6).

**Standard entry (Self-Critic Pass passed):**

```markdown
### - [ ] Lines X-Y: [Brief description] `[Critical|High|Medium|Low]`

**Comment:** [Why this is AI-typical]

**Original:**
```
[Full sentence(s) containing the issue — never fragments]
```

**Proposed Revision:**
```
[Complete revised sentence(s)]
```

**Why better:** [Explanation]
```

**Flag-only entry (Self-Critic Pass failed — use when any structural test fails):**

```markdown
### - [ ] Lines X-Y: [Brief description] `[Critical|High|Medium|Low]`

**Comment:** [Why this is AI-typical]

**Original:**
```
[Full sentence(s)]
```

**Why no rewrite:** [One sentence: which test failed — e.g., "Rewrite traded `speak to` for `illuminate` — same register, no clarity gain."]

**Self-screen:** rewrite withheld — [reason]
```

---

## Quality Control

- [ ] `ai_detection.md`: Pattern identification appended (not overwritten)
- [ ] `simplifications.md`: Suggested fixes appended (not overwritten)
- [ ] Section header `## [filename.tex]` in both files
- [ ] Part A (punctuation/structure) comprehensive
- [ ] **R-COLON exhaustively flagged** — every body-prose colon construction listed (single occurrence = High; 2+ in same passage = Critical). Do not skip "low-impact" instances.
- [ ] Part B (language) comprehensive — especially smarmy reframing and stacked hedges (R-HEDGE)
- [ ] Part C (rhetorical/argument) comprehensive — especially missing mechanisms and results-first openings
- [ ] Each flagged entry has a severity tier label (`Critical`, `High`, `Medium`, or `Low`)
- [ ] Entries sorted by severity (Critical → High → Medium → Low) within each file section
- [ ] Each item has Comment/Original/Proposed/Why better
- [ ] Every Proposed Revision passed the full Self-Critic Pass (Tests 1–6) — surface critic ran on each
- [ ] Items that failed Self-Critic Pass structurally use the flag-only entry shape (no Proposed Revision block)
- [ ] R-WEAK-FOR-WEAK enforced on every revision
- [ ] R-NEW-CLAIMS enforced on every revision
- [ ] Fixes are SUGGESTIONS only — not auto-applied to .tex files

### LLM Section Checklist (verify by rule ID)

Before finalizing flags for any LLM-tagged or suspected-LLM section, verify these rules and patterns are enforced. Bodies are in `writing_quality_standards.md`.

- [ ] R-RAP — does the opening create tension, or just announce the topic? (Introduction context)
- [ ] R-TRIANGULAR — body paragraphs state result before mechanism
- [ ] Sentence length varies (sentence_analysis owns the metric; flag here only if rhythm violations interact with an AI tell)
- [ ] Every number answers "so what?" (Principle 7)
- [ ] R-HEDGE — no paragraph carries more than two hedges
- [ ] R-TRANSITION — no sentence-initial Moreover/Furthermore/etc. that could be deleted
- [ ] Mechanism Over Description (Principle 2) — causal chain explicit, not just outcomes
- [ ] Footnote strategy — minor caveats in footnotes, not inline (Contrast II.8)
- [ ] **R-COLON** — every body-prose `CLAUSE: CLAUSE` and `CLAUSE: A, B, C` flagged exhaustively. Single occurrence = High; 2+ in same passage = Critical.
- [ ] Match Claims to Evidence (Principle 15) — no verb overshoots the identification strategy
- [ ] R-DEMONSTRATIVE — bare this/these/that/those have noun referents (3+ in a paragraph = High)
- [ ] Technical terms (strategic complementarities, moral hazard, adverse selection, GE effects) used per their formal definitions
- [ ] Overall: would a reader familiar with LLM writing recognize this as AI-generated?

**Note:** Items flagged in Part C are quick pattern detections. The `writing_quality` task (Sonnet) provides definitive paragraph-level assessment with actionable rewrites. When both tasks flag the same passage, `writing_quality` takes precedence during wrapup deduplication.
